)\")]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"li\",[e._v(\"Holonomic Drive\")]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"li\",[e._v(\"Mecanum Drive\")])]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"p\",[a(\"strong\",[e._v(\"Tank Drive\")])]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"p\",[e._v(\"A simple, beginner-friendly design, the “tank” drive, as it is affectionately named, allows for easy construction and programming.\")]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"p\",[a(\"img\",{attrs:{src:i(359),alt:\"An Image\"}})]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"p\",[e._v(\"(A simple example of a tank drive (with chains for motor efficiency) Dwayne Lemos, 2019)\")]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"p\",[e._v(\"Tank drives are quite versatile, and can be used as a simple push-bot (a robot with the sole purpose of pushing objects around the play area), or can be built upon for a complex system. They can be built in as little as an hour (like the example shown above) with very few frills, yet provide a stable and dependable platform. This means they are generally the design of choice for newer teams.\")]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"p\",[e._v(\"Opposing sides of a tank drive base have wheels or tank treads or a combination of both. Moving the opposite sides in the same direction moves the robot forward and back, while rotating them in opposite directions causes the robot to rotate.\")]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"p\",[e._v(\"Logically, using certain wheels will provide certain turning characteristics – traction wheels will not allow for easy turning, as they are designed for single-axis movement. However, using omni wheels, with multi-direction motion, smooth turning can be achieved. This is the wheel of choice for most teams in most circumstances, although it leaves the robot open to unwanted lateral movement in competition. Additionally, variations include 6- and 8-wheel drive as well as wheels at different heights for climbing.\")]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"p\",[a(\"img\",{attrs:{src:i(360),alt:\"An Image\"}})]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"p\",[e._v(\"(Tank drives generally only have front-back mobility with 4 traction wheels)\")]),e._v(\" \"),a(\"p\",[a(\"img\",{attrs:{sr